Your goal in the Darwinian Networks Lab is to explain how evolution reached a final specific stage spending the minimum amount of energy as possible.
You can explain evolution by manipulating populations.
Populations contain combative and docile traits, represented by a filled and unfilled colour, respectively.
Darwinian Networks (DNs) simplify working with Bayesian networks (BNs). BNs are a probabilistic graphical model used in artificial intelligence for uncertainty management.

DNs adapt a handful of well-known concepts in biology into a single framework that is surprisingly simple, yet remarkably robust. A conditional probability table P(X|Y) is viewed as a population p(X,Y) with combative traits X and docile traits Y. More generally, a BN is seen as a set of populations. Abstract concepts like merge and replication are used to represent multiplication, division, and addition. Good elimination orderings, which are of practical importance, can be computed in DNs with the concept of energy.
